{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"13c8533f-5b2c-42c9-90a1-b892b8a8aff0","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, so here's the answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** — macOS writes cores to `/cores/` by default. Verify with:\n   ```\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Ensure SIP allows core dumps** — on modern macOS, System Integrity Protection may block core file generation. Check with `csrutil status`. You may need to boot into Recovery Mode to adjust settings.\n\n4. **Use macOS's built-in crash reports** — even without a core dump, macOS writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces, register state, and loaded images.\n\n5. **Use `lldb` post-mortem** — if you have a core file:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> <your-app-binary>\n   ```\n\n6. **For NativeAOT specifically** — since `createdump` is a CoreCLR tool and isn't shipped with NativeAOT, the OS-level core dump (`/cores/`) is your primary mechanism. Make sure your app is published with debug symbols (`.dsym`) so `lldb` can symbolicate the stack.\n\n**TL;DR:** Rely on `ulimit -c unlimited` + `/cores/` for full core dumps, and `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for Apple's built-in crash reports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ad42cc56-39f2-4343-aa16-5573a1592be4","outputTokens":399,"requestId":"943E:2E7204:27EA37:2F4B09:69E82065"},"id":"cf3b11b3-8e5a-42ea-8b63-4939c4cfdc28","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:12:17.830Z","parentId":"097e167b-f0ac-4ddb-96f2-2364e53ec102"}
